Originally, temnospondyls were classified according to the structure of their vertebrae. Early forms, with complex vertebrae consisting of a number of separate elements, were placed in the suborder Rachitomi, and large Triassic aquatic forms with simpler vertebrae were placed in the suborder Stereospondyli. With the recent growth of phylogenetics, this classification is no longer viable. The basic rhachitomous condition is found in many primitive tetrapods, and is not unique to one group of temnospondyls. Moreover, the distinction between rhachitomous and stereospondylic vertebrae is not as clear as it was in the past, as many tetrapods have either a rhachitomous or a stereospondylic vertebra. For example, Ambulocetosaurus, an early amniote, has a rhachitomous vertebra, but most later amniotes have a stereospondylic vertebra. This discovery was also significant in that it clearly established the presence of early tetrapods in the Late Triassic, which had been previously unknown.
